What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset - MyData has 4898 white wines(observations) with 13 features (variables). The column names of these variables are: fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol, and quality

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features of interest are quality, residual sugar, alcohol and acids - which I think play the biggest role in the quality of wine. The objective of the analysis is to determine what features influence wine quality the most; then a predictive model of quality using these variables will be built.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed.

How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?
The question being addressed here is how quality varied in relation to fixed acidity, residual sugar, free.sulphurdioxide, total.sulphurdioxide, density and chloride.

Fixed acidity and citric acid show a U-like pattern! starting from a high value of 0.345g/dm^3 with quality 3, the citric acid is lowered to 0.32 and gradually increased to 0.36 at quality level 9. The increase shows an in the quality.

Residual sugar - is sugar left over after fermentation. There is no clear trend here. However Sugar content decreases from 7 at quality 5 to 2.2 g/dm^3 at 9. This is telling us that the best quality wine has less sugar.
But again it depends on ones taste because quality 8 has a sugar level twice as much as that at nine.

Free Sulphur dioxide: The wine quality from 5 - 9 shows a trend from 35 to 28 mg/dm^3;showing that a decrease within this range improves quality. A similar trend is shown by the total sulphates since they both work as antioxidants and preservatives of wine.

Density: a decrease in density from 0.9953 to 0.9903 corresponds to a quality increase of 5 to 9. It makes sense since density results from a combination of alcohol and sugar. And we see that density changes correspond to the changes both in alcohol and sugar. This is confirmed by the high positive correlation of density and sugar of 0.84.

An increase in alcohol content supports increased wine quality from 5 - 9. While a decrease in the amount of chlorides which are essentially salts supports improved wine quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)? Yee - its interesting to note that an

increase in alcohol improves quality. Note that the high correlation of residual sugar with density is due to the combination of both the residual sugar and alcohol.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship is that of residual sugar and density which gives a positive correlation of 0.84.

Building the linear model

To create a linear model I will use the lm function. Density is the outcome and residual sugar is the predictor variable. Note the use of the I Wrapper around each of the variables.

I can also update the previous model to add another factor in the regression (using the syntax below). We can continue to make more complex models by adding more variables (chlorides, free.sulphurdioxide, fixed acidity, residual sugar etc).

## 
## Calls:
## m1: lm(formula = I(log(density)) ~ I(residual.sugar), data = MyData)
## m2: lm(formula = I(log(density)) ~ I(residual.sugar) + residual.sugar, 
##     data = MyData)
## m3: lm(formula = I(log(density)) ~ I(residual.sugar) + residual.sugar + 
##     total.sulfur.dioxide, data = MyData)
## m4: lm(formula = I(log(density)) ~ I(residual.sugar) + residual.sugar + 
##     total.sulfur.dioxide + fixed.acidity, data = MyData)
## m5: lm(formula = I(log(density)) ~ I(residual.sugar) + residual.sugar + 
##     total.sulfur.dioxide + fixed.acidity + chlorides, data = MyData)
## m6: lm(formula = I(log(density)) ~ I(residual.sugar) + residual.sugar + 
##     total.sulfur.dioxide + fixed.acidity + chlorides + pH, data = MyData)
## m7: lm(formula = I(log(density)) ~ I(residual.sugar) + residual.sugar + 
##     total.sulfur.dioxide + fixed.acidity + chlorides + pH + alcohol, 
##     data = MyData)
## m8: lm(formula = I(log(density)) ~ I(residual.sugar) + residual.sugar + 
##     total.sulfur.dioxide + fixed.acidity + chlorides + pH + alcohol + 
##     sulphates, data = MyData)
## m9: lm(formula = I(log(density)) ~ I(residual.sugar) + residual.sugar + 
##     total.sulfur.dioxide + fixed.acidity + chlorides + pH + alcohol + 
##     sulphates + citric.acid, data = MyData)

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
Yes - a Model was built for density vs residual sugar vs quality. Based on the

R2 score, residual sugar alone explains about 70.3% of the variance in quality. The high positive correlation between density and sugar in the matrix already hinted on this.

Strengths and limitations of your model.

Decision models are increasingly powerful for tasks requiring the impartial analysis of vast amounts of data. The beauty of this model is that it allows us to gather and process vast amounts of information/factors in one place. The model also enables one to select the number of variables to use - in this case, I added 10 variables from the dataset. And such a model is not biases against anything like the recent wine it took or whether it got up on the wrong side of the bed. This model weighs all data objectively and evenly.

The limitation is that it needs vast amounts of information and can not directly influence the process to give the desired outcome.

They can predict the quality of a wine vintage but wont make the wine any better, reduce its acidity, improve the balance, or change the undertones. For these sorts of estimates, finding ways to avoid bias and maintain accuracy is essential.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

Residual sugar data is skewed to the right with the centre at 5.2g/dm^3. Note the outliers especially about zero . To see the distribution better, the data is transformed using Log 10 scale. This gives a bimodal distribution as shown. The max sugar can be 65 but most wines have a value less than 15. Note the outlier near zero.

Plot Two

Description Two

This is an interesting plot becuase it shows that the density of all wines is almost the same. Secondly it demonstrates how small minor changes in density affect wine quality.

Plot Three

Description Three

This is an interesting plot! - the red line clearly divides quality into 2 groups; The plot clearly shows the less density fines have better quality than the denser ones above the line. Density & residual sugar dynamics are therefor a good choice in determining wine quality. I am confident that this makes a good model.

Reflection

What a journey! Its great to come to a close, I have certainly been challenged and had fun too. I have had to reset my PC to factory standard twice to remove one drive and delet it from the path of my downloads. Debugging errors would sometimes take ages than was necessary. Other than that it was partly an easy trip because the dataset is clean and almost no data wrangling was
necessary. Making the different plots, the adjustment, transformations and interpretion - has been a valuable experience.

The systematic exploration of the dataset from univariates to bivariates and finally multivariates helped me to progressively understand the dataset. Uncovering insights especially when relating two variables and more was interesting. Now I have a good understanding of how the different variables in wine interact with each other to produce wine. Its interesting to see how minor changes like with density or alchohol - can determine the quality of wine. Quality is subjective. Striking a good balance is key.

What went well for me and what gave me the best feeling was when I built my model and understood that indeed the parameters I had zeroed in, one of them - residual sugar alone explains about 70.3% of the variance in quality. This was surprising!

I believe that there is always room for improvement. This dataset can be made richer by adding external variables like soil type, variety of the grape, weather etc. With that said, Wine quality is definately a very subjective measure.
While beauty depends on the eyes of the beholder, wine depends on the palate of the individual!
